To handle parallel processing where you need a response back from each thread, we need to upgrade our approach slightly. Instead of just submitting a Runnable (which returns void and fires-and-forgets), we will submit a Callable. This allows each virtual thread to return a Future containing the results from System B.
Here is the complete implementation using Guava for partitioning and the invokeAll method to cleanly gather all responses.
1. Maven Dependency (Guava)
Make sure you have Guava in your pom.xml (or build.gradle):
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.google.guava</groupId>
    <artifactId>guava</artifactId>
    <version>33.0.0-jre</version> </dependency>

2. The Complete Implementation
import com.google.common.collect.Lists;

import java.time.Duration;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.concurrent.Callable;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;
import java.util.concurrent.Future;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;
import java.util.stream.IntStream;

public class VirtualThreadBatchProcessor {

    // --- Domain Objects ---
    public record Person(long id, String name) {}
    public record SystemBResponse(long personId, boolean success, String errorMessage) {}

    private static final int BATCH_SIZE = 100;

    public void processPersonsAndCollectResults(List<Person> allPersons) {
        System.out.println("Preparing to send " + allPersons.size() + " records to System B...");

        // 1. Partition the list using Guava
        List<List<Person>> batches = Lists.partition(allPersons, BATCH_SIZE);

        // 2. Map each batch to a Callable task that returns a List of Responses
        List<Callable<List<SystemBResponse>>> tasks = batches.stream()
                .map(batch -> (Callable<List<SystemBResponse>>) () -> sendBatchToSystemB(batch))
                .toList();

        List<SystemBResponse> allResults = new ArrayList<>();

        // 3. Execute with Virtual Threads
        try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
            
            // invokeAll blocks the main thread until ALL virtual threads have finished their work
            List<Future<List<SystemBResponse>>> futures = executor.invokeAll(tasks);

            // 4. Aggregate the results
            for (Future<List<SystemBResponse>> future : futures) {
                // future.get() is immediately available because invokeAll already waited
                List<SystemBResponse> batchResult = future.get(); 
                allResults.addAll(batchResult);
            }

        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.err.println("A critical error occurred during batch processing: " + e.getMessage());
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        }

        // 5. Analyze the final results
        long successCount = allResults.stream().filter(SystemBResponse::success).count();
        long failureCount = allResults.size() - successCount;
        
        System.out.println("\n--- Final Processing Report ---");
        System.out.println("Total Processed: " + allResults.size());
        System.out.println("Successful: " + successCount);
        System.out.println("Failed: " + failureCount);
    }

    /**
     * Mocks the external API call to System B.
     * This runs inside the Virtual Thread.
     */
    private List<SystemBResponse> sendBatchToSystemB(List<Person> batch) {
        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread() + " sending batch of " + batch.size());
        
        try {
            // Simulate network latency (Virtual Thread unmounts here)
            Thread.sleep(Duration.ofMillis(800)); 
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
            throw new RuntimeException("Batch interrupted", e);
        }

        // Simulate System B processing and returning a response for each Person
        return batch.stream()
                .map(person -> {
                    // Let's pretend IDs divisible by 15 cause a failure in System B
                    boolean isSuccess = person.id() % 15 != 0; 
                    String error = isSuccess ? null : "Validation failed in System B";
                    return new SystemBResponse(person.id(), isSuccess, error);
                })
                .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Generate 2000 dummy persons
        List<Person> persons = IntStream.rangeClosed(1, 2000)
                .mapToObj(i -> new Person(i, "Person " + i))
                .toList();

        VirtualThreadBatchProcessor processor = new VirtualThreadBatchProcessor();
        processor.processPersonsAndCollectResults(persons);
    }
}

Why this design is effective:
 * No Shared State: We completely avoided thread synchronization issues (like ConcurrentModificationException) by having each thread return its own independent list of results, rather than trying to add() to a shared list concurrently.
 * invokeAll: This is the most powerful method when you need all results. It fires off all the tasks simultaneously and waits for the very last one to finish before returning the list of Future objects.
 * Clean Data Contracts: Using Java Records (Person and SystemBResponse) keeps the data immutable and the memory footprint minimal, which is exactly what you want when handling thousands of objects in memory.
